GESIS CSS strategy development

Bennett Kleinberg

20 Sept.2022

Long-term vision

Research excellence

Impact through world-leading research.

  • fundamental, methodological questions
  • topical questions
  • from exploring and describing to understanding
    • CSS theories
    • psychometrics of digital behavioural data

Outstanding services

World-leading research through outstanding services.

  • capacities beyond single university efforts
  • closing the gap between disciplines
  • breaking down the infrastructural barriers
    • data access
    • available methods
    • knowledge transfer

Achieving this vision

Setting a goal

What is the goal of CSS?

that makes GESIS unique?

A moonshot goal

(Very) ambitious goal that guides (\(\neq\) determines) all efforts.

  • common in other disciplines (medicine, public health), industry and transnational bodies (UN Sustainable Development Goals)
  • but practically absent in social science research

Examples: end malnutrition by 2030, doubling cancer survival

CSS can be bold.

1. A CSS moonshot goal

Understanding the nexus between offline and online human behaviour.

Implies:

  • new funding (macro and micro) for internal teams to contribute to this goal
  • alignment of staff recruitment toward that goal
  • make the overarching goal the identifying and distinguishing characteristic of CSS at GESIS
  • the existing structures are an excellent starting point to make bold moves

2. Wild ideas

Most undervalued resource: seemingly pointless ideas.

  • traditional model is hostile to wild ideas
  • but: many wild ideas are not so pointless in hindsight

Proposal:

  • central part of CSS: the Wild Ideas Lab
  • unbureaucratic access to time and funding
  • work on wild ideas with minimal oversight

Example: exploring a new method for 1 day/week for 3 months with a student assistant.

3. Service incubator

The service mission is a pillar of CSS.

  • a dual task load (research + services) is a delicate balancing act for teams and individuals

Proposal:

  • more attention to services with a CSS Service Incubator
  • equal to pure research teams but as an in-house start-up
  • full dedication to the professionalisation of services (video portals, course material, software)
  • close collaboration with research teams

4. Behavioural inference team

Human behaviour is the key frontier for CSS.

  • digital behavioural data are exciting but (very) challenging
  • needs a dedicated focus

Proposal:

  • new research team on behavioural inference
  • closely aligned to social science methods (experiments)
  • using the integrative modelling approach

Structure after proposal

5. Talent development

Talent is the one most valuable resource for CSS.

Proposal:

  • fostering talent through ambition-based development
  • harnessing wild ideas
  • talent as the stakeholder of GESIS

Do we even need CSS?

Yes. But not because its a fascinating area to work on.

More important: CSS can solve the hard societal problems

The ultimate goal of CSS must be social impact.

Full commitment to the two most precious resources:

ideas + talent
